==English==

===Alternative spellings===
* [[ilke]]

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|ilke|lang=enm}} < {{etyl|ang}} {{term|īlca|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|ilikaz|lang=en}}, a compound of {{proto|Germanic|title=|lang=en|i-}} and {{proto|Germanic|title=|lang=en|-likaz}} from the noun {{proto|Germanic|title=|lang=en|likam|body}}.

The sense of “type”, “kind” is from the application of the phrase ‘{{term|of that ilk}}’ to families: the word thus came to mean ‘{{term|family}}’.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ɪlk/}}
* {{audio|en-us-ilk.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*: {{rhymes|ɪlk}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|-}}

# {{context|Scottish|and|Northern England}} The [[same]].

====Usage notes====
Used following a person’s name to show that he lives in a place of the same name, eg ''Johnstone of that ilk'' means ''Johnstone of Johnstone''.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[type]], [[race]] or [[category]]; a group of entities that have common characteristics such that they may be grouped together.
#* '''1906''' — [[w:Upton Sinclair|Upton Sinclair]], ''[[s:The Jungle|The Jungle]]'', Ch. 25
#*: ''“Hinkydink” or “Bathhouse John,” or others of that '''ilk''', were proprietors of the most notorious dives in Chicago...''

====Usage notes====
*Most frequently used in the phrase {{term|of that ilk}}.

